data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already threw `InvalidOperationException` for sync operations by default, but you could suppress it:

```csharp
options.ConfigureWarnings(w => w.Ignore(CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported));
```

**In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** The sync-over-async code path is gone from the Cosmos provider—suppressing the warning no longer has any effect. All four of your methods (`ToList`, `First`, `Count`, `SaveChanges`) will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime with no workaround.

## The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key steps:**
1. Remove the `CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported` suppression from your `DbContext` config — it's a no-op now.
2. Convert all sync LINQ/persistence calls to their `*Async` counterparts.
3. Propagate `async/await` up through your call chain (controllers, services, etc.).
